SIMPLE: infuse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infuse
<hw>In*fuse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Infused</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Infusing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>infusus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>infundere</ets> to pour in or into; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>fundere</ets> to pour: cf. F. <ets>infuser</ets>. See
<er>Found</er> to cast.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pour in, as a liquid;
to pour (into or upon); to shed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That strong Circean liquor cease to <qex>infuse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To instill, as principles or qualities; to
introduce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That souls of animals <qex>infuse</qex> themselves Into the trunks
of men.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why should he desire to have qualities <qex>infused</qex> into his
son which himself never possessed?</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To inspire; to inspirit or animate; to fill; --
followed by <xex>with</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Infuse</qex> his breast with magnanimity.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Infusing</qex> him with self and vain conceit.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To steep in water or other fluid without boiling,
for the propose of extracting medicinal qualities; to soak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One scruple of dried leaves is <qex>infused</qex> in ten ounces of
warm water.</q> <rj><qau>Coxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make an infusion with, as an ingredient; to
tincture; to saturate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infuse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Infuse
<hw>In*fuse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Infusion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infuser</ent>⟦br⟧
